04441nam a22007095i 9780674040892DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222003mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740408927 a10.4159/97806740408922doi  a(DE-B1597)617426  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aKF2979b.M37 2001 7aLAW0500002bisacsh04a346.7304/82211 aMcSherry, Corynne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWho Owns Academic Work? :bBattling for Control of Intellectual Property /cCorynne McSherry. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACRONYMS -- tIntroduction -- t1. Building an Epistemic Regime -- t2. An Uncommon Controversy -- t3. “University Lectures Are Sui Generis” -- t4. Metes and Bounds -- t5. Telling Tales Out of School -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWho owns academic work? This question is provoking political and legal battles, fought on uncertain terrain, for ever-higher stakes. The posting of faculty lecture notes on commercial Web sites is being hotly debated in multiple forums, even as faculty and university administrators square off in a battle for professorial copyright. In courtrooms throughout the country, universities find themselves embroiled in intricate and expensive patent litigation. Meanwhile, junior researchers are appearing in those same courtrooms, using intellectual property rules to challenge traditional academic hierarchies. All but forgotten in these ownership disputes is a more fundamental question: should academic work be owned at all? Once characterized as a kind of gift, academic work--and academic freedom--are now being reframed as private intellectual property. Drawing on legal, historical, and qualitative research, Corynne McSherry explores the propertization of academic work and shows how that process is shaking the foundations of the university, the professoriate, and intellectual property law. The modern university's reason for being is inextricably tied to that of the intellectual property system. The rush of universities and scholars to defend their knowledge as property dangerously undercuts a working covenant that has sustained academic life--and intellectual property law--for a century and a half. As the value structure of the research university is replaced by the inequalities of the free market, academics risk losing a language for talking about knowledge as anything other than property. McSherry has written a book that ought to deeply trouble everyone who cares about the academy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aAcademic freedomzUnited States. 0aCopyrightzUnited States. 0aIntellectual propertyzUnited States. 0aPublic domain (Copyright law)zUnited States. 0aScholarly publishingzUnited States. 7aLAW / Intellectual Property / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674040892zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674040892423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674040892/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK